DNS Amplification and Reflection Security Research Report

The Domain Name System (DNS) is a foundational Internet protocol responsible for translating human-readable domain names into IP addresses. Its distributed and high-performance architecture allows the Internet to scale globally. However, certain properties of DNS — particularly its use of the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) — have historically enabled misuse in the form of reflection and amplification attacks.
DNS amplification attacks occur when small DNS queries generate disproportionately large responses that are directed toward a third party. This behavior typically involves misconfigured DNS infrastructure known as open recursive resolvers.

This report provides overview of:

• DNS protocol design
• Reflection and amplification mechanics
• Packet structure and amplification math
• Internet measurement methodologies
• Historical attack incidents
• Security mitigation techniques
• Future challenges for DNS infrastructure

The objective is to provide a detailed technical understanding of DNS amplification vulnerabilities and the steps necessary to mitigate them.
1. DNS Protocol Architecture
    1.1 DNS Overview
The Domain Name System provides a hierarchical, distributed naming system used to resolve domain names into network addresses.

example.com = 93.184.216.34

DNS enables:
• domain name resolution
• service discovery
• email routing
• infrastructure redundancy
1.2 DNS Hierarchy
DNS operates using a hierarchical delegation model(HDH)

User Device
     │
     ▼
Recursive Resolver
     │
     ▼
Root Name Server
     │
     ▼
Top Level Domain (TLD) Server
     │
     ▼
Authoritative Name Server

Stub Resolver: Software on a client device that initiates DNS queries.
Recursive Resolver: Server that performs the complete lookup process on behalf of the client.
Root Servers: Top of the DNS hierarchy that direct queries to appropriate TLD servers.
TLD Servers: Responsible for domains such as: .com|.org|.net|.uk.
Authoritative Servers: Provide definitive answers for domain records.

2. DNS Transport Protocols
DNS supports two primary transport protocols.
UDP – primary protocol for standard queries
TCP – used for zone transfers and large responses

2.1 UDP Characteristics

UDP is used because it provides:

• minimal overhead
• low latency
• stateless communication
• high scalability

UDP communication flow:
Client → DNS Query
Server → DNS Response
Unlike TCP, UDP does not require a connection handshake.
TCP handshake: SYN > SYN/ACK > ACK
UDP exchange: Query > Response
Because of this efficiency, DNS over UDP is extremely fast.
However, UDP introduces a critical property:
The server does not verify the sender identity.
The server simply replies to the source IP address contained in the packet header.
3. Reflection and Amplification
3.1 Reflection Concept
Reflection occurs when a server sends traffic to a third party rather than the true sender.
Example model:
Attacker → DNS Query (spoofed source)
           │
           ▼
       DNS Resolver
           │
           ▼
        Victim System

The resolver believes it is replying to the legitimate sender.
3.2 Amplification Concept
Amplification occurs when the response generated by a request is significantly larger than the request itself.
Example:
DNS Query      60–80 bytes
DNS Response   2000–4000 bytes

Amplification formula:

Amplification Ratio = Response Size / Request Size

Example calculation:
Query Size:      70 bytes
Response Size:  2800 bytes
Amplification = 2800 / 70
Amplification ≈ 40x

