5. DNS Query and Response Size

Typical DNS query size:
IP Header       20 bytes
UDP Header       8 bytes
DNS Header      12 bytes
QNAME          ~15 bytes
QTYPE/QCLASS    4 bytes

Total ≈ 60–80 bytes
Typical DNS responses can be much larger.
A record response        ~100 bytes
MX record response       ~200 bytes
DNSSEC response         1500–3000 bytes
Large TXT record        2000+ bytes

6. EDNS and Large Responses
Original DNS limited UDP responses to: 512 bytes
Modern DNS uses EDNS (Extension Mechanisms for DNS).

Common EDNS buffer sizes:
512 bytes,1232 bytes,2048 bytes,4096 bytes
These larger responses support:
DNSSEC signatures,IPv6 records,Large TXT records, DNSKEY record sets
However, they also increase potential amplification ratios.

7. Open Recursive Resolvers
An open resolver answers recursive queries from any Internet host.
Example insecure configuration:
allow-recursion { any; };
Secure configuration example:
allow-recursion {
    localhost;
    localnets;
};
Reasons open resolvers exist:
• legacy DNS configurations
• consumer routers exposing DNS
• ISP infrastructure errors
• outdated software defaults
These systems can unintentionally reflect traffic.

 8. Internet-Scale Amplification
Large attacks may involve thousands of DNS resolvers simultaneously
Simplified attack topology:
Attacker
   │
   ├── Resolver A
   ├── Resolver B
   ├── Resolver C
   └── Resolver D
           │
           ▼
         Target
Each resolver sends a response toward the target.
Combined traffic can reach extremely large volumes.

