12. Security Mitigations
12.1 Disable Open Recursion
Resolvers should restrict recursion to trusted networks.
allow-recursion {
    localnets;
    localhost;
};
12.2 Response Rate Limiting (RRL)
Modern DNS servers implement response throttling.
Concept: If identical responses exceed threshold, responses are rate limited
Benefits:
limits abuse
reduces amplification potential

12.3 Source Address Validation (BCP38)
Best Current Practice 38 recommends **ingress filtering**.
Routers verify outgoing packets contain valid source addresses.
Invalid source → packet dropped
Wide deployment would eliminate reflection attacks entirely.
12.4 EDNS Response Size Limits
Operators may reduce EDNS buffer sizes.
Example:
max-udp-size 1232
This limits maximum amplification.

13. Improvements in DNS Security
Over the past decade significant improvements have occurred.
• reduction in open resolvers
• better DNS software defaults
• widespread rate limiting
• increased ISP filtering

Major DNS software implementing protections:
BIND | Unbound | PowerDNS | Knot DNS

14. Future Challenges
Despite progress, several challenges remain in this area of security:
 legacy infrastructure, misconfigured routers, incomplete BCP38 deployment(that's the main thing that allows this attack to work), growing DNSSEC usage. Continuous monitoring and research remain essential.

15. Responsible Security Research
Ethical DNS research follows established principles.
1) obtain authorization
2) avoid service disruption
3) limit testing intensity
4) disclose findings responsibly

Responsible research helps improve the security of the global Internet.

16. Conclusion

DNS amplification is not a flaw in DNS itself but rather a combination of protocol design choices and infrastructure misconfiguration.
The vulnerability emerges when: UDP reflection is possible, large DNS responses exist, resolvers allow unrestricted recursion
Through improved configuration practices, network filtering, and rate limiting, the Internet community has significantly reduced the risk posed by DNS amplification attacks. Continued collaboration between researchers, network operators, and software developers remains essential to maintain the resilience of the global DNS ecosystem.
